\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Future trajectory\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 What plausibly changes for MCP over the next decade:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 1. Continued monitoring
\f0\b0  of the existing 6 galaxies will tighten distances. Acceleration measurements improve with the square root of monitoring time, so doubling the baseline (~5 more years of GBT + VLBA observations) tightens per-galaxy distance precision by ~30%. Combined with the existing PV systematic, this might bring the standalone MCP H\uc0\u8320  from \'b13.0 to ~\'b12.5. Useful but not transformative.\

\f1\b 2. New megamaser searches
\f0\b0  with more sensitive single-dish instruments could find more disks. The pre-ngVLA era likely sees ~1\'962 new MCP-quality systems added; ngVLA itself (with ~10\'d7 sensitivity at 22 GHz) might add ~10+ systems over its operational lifetime.\

\f1\b 3. Improved peculiar velocity models.
\f0\b0  DESI's redshift-space distortion data and new bulk-flow reconstructions are improving the local PV field substantially. Within ~5 years, the per-galaxy PV uncertainty for MCP targets could drop from \'b1250 km/s to \'b1150 km/s. This alone would tighten MCP H\uc0\u8320  to ~\'b12.0.\

\f1\b 4. The ngVLA-era projection.
\f0\b0  With ~30 megamaser disks suitable for VLBI mapping (the optimistic ngVLA-era projection) and improved PV models, MCP could plausibly reach 1\'962% standalone H\uc0\u8320  precision by ~2040. This would make it competitive with SH0ES on its own terms \'97 geometric, ladder-free, completely independent.\
For your EDE-relevant timescale (paper this year, future work over the next few years), the practical state of MCP is roughly fixed. The 73.9 \'b1 3.0 standalone value will tighten modestly but won't transform. The NGC 4258 anchor will tighten somewhat but won't transform either. So MCP enters your inference as a relatively stable, modestly informative likelihood that mostly does its work via the NGC 4258 anchor on other measurements.\
